# AWS Practical: Secure VPC Architecture with Bastion Host

## Question

Create a VPC named `Lab_VPC_<PRN>` with CIDR block `10.0.0.0/16`.

Create:

* Public Subnet: `10.0.1.0/24`
* Private Subnet: `10.0.2.0/24`

Attach an Internet Gateway and configure route tables so that only the Public Subnet has Internet access.

Launch:

* One EC2 in Public Subnet (Bastion Host)
* One EC2 in Private Subnet

Configure Security Groups so that:

* Public EC2 is accessible from local machine using SSH.
* Private EC2 is accessible only from Public EC2.

Create a file containing your PRN number on Public EC2, transfer it securely to Private EC2 and verify the contents.



# Step 1: Create VPC

AWS Console → VPC → Create VPC

```text
Name: Lab_VPC_<PRN>
CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16
```

---

# Step 2: Create Public Subnet

```text
Name: Public-Subnet
CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24
```

---

# Step 3: Create Private Subnet

```text
Name: Private-Subnet
CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24
```

---

# Step 4: Create Internet Gateway

```text
Name: Lab-IGW
```

Attach to:

```text
Lab_VPC_<PRN>
```

---

# Step 5: Create Public Route Table

Create Route Table:

```text
Public-RT
```

Add Route:

```text
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: Internet Gateway
```

Associate:

```text
Public-Subnet
```

---

# Step 6: Configure Private Route Table

Associate:

```text
Private-Subnet
```

Do NOT add:

```text
0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway
```

Result:

```text
Private subnet has no direct Internet access.
```

---

# Step 7: Create Bastion Security Group

Name:

```text
Bastion-SG
```

Inbound Rule:

| Type | Port | Source |
| ---- | ---- | ------ |
| SSH  | 22   | My IP  |

Outbound Rule:

| Type        | Destination |
| ----------- | ----------- |
| All Traffic | 0.0.0.0/0   |

---

# Step 8: Create Private Security Group

Name:

```text
Private-SG
```

Inbound Rule:

| Type | Port | Source     |
| ---- | ---- | ---------- |
| SSH  | 22   | Bastion-SG |

Outbound Rule:

| Type        | Destination |
| ----------- | ----------- |
| All Traffic | 0.0.0.0/0   |

---

# Step 9: Launch Public EC2

Configuration:

```text
Name: Public-EC2
AMI: Amazon Linux 2023
Instance Type: t2.micro
Key Pair: public
```

Network:

```text
VPC: Lab_VPC_<PRN>
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto Assign Public IP: Enable
Security Group: Bastion-SG
```

---

# Step 10: Launch Private EC2

IMPORTANT:

Use SAME Key Pair as Public EC2.

```text
Key Pair: public
```

Network:

```text
VPC: Lab_VPC_<PRN>
Subnet: Private-Subnet
Auto Assign Public IP: Disable
Security Group: Private-SG
```

---

# Step 11: SSH from Windows to Public EC2

Find Public IPv4 Address.

PowerShell:

```powershell
ssh -i "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" ec2-user@65.0.87.192
```

Expected:

```bash
[ec2-user@ip-10-0-1-x ~]$
```

---

# Windows Permission Fix

If error appears:

```text
UNPROTECTED PRIVATE KEY FILE
```

Run:

```powershell
icacls "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" /inheritance:r

icacls "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" /grant:r "Abhishek:(R)"

icacls "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" /remove "Authenticated Users" "Users" "Everyone"
```

Then SSH again.

---

# Step 12: Copy PEM to Public EC2

Open new PowerShell window:

```powershell
scp -i "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" "D:\Users\ABHISHEK KUMAR\Downloads\public.pem" ec2-user@65.0.87.192:/home/ec2-user/
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -l public.pem
```

Fix permissions:

```bash
chmod 400 public.pem
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -l public.pem
```

Output:

```text
-r-------- public.pem
```

---

# Step 13: Find Private EC2 IP

AWS Console → Instances → Private-EC2

Example:

```text
10.0.2.90
```

---

# Step 14: SSH Public EC2 → Private EC2

```bash
ssh -i public.pem ec2-user@10.0.2.90
```

Expected:

```bash
[ec2-user@ip-10-0-2-x ~]$
```

---

# Common Mistake

If Private EC2 was launched using a different key pair:

```text
Permission denied (publickey)
```

Solution:

```text
Terminate Private EC2
Launch new Private EC2
Use SAME key pair as Public EC2
```

---

# Step 15: Create PRN File

On Public EC2:

```bash
echo "PRN: 240340120001" > prn.txt
```

Verify:

```bash
cat prn.txt
```

Output:

```text
PRN: 240340120001
```

---

# Step 16: Transfer File

```bash
scp -i public.pem prn.txt ec2-user@10.0.2.90:/home/ec2-user/
```

---

# Step 17: Verify File

Login to Private EC2:

```bash
ssh -i public.pem ec2-user@10.0.2.90
```

Check:

```bash
cat prn.txt
```

Expected:

```text
PRN: 240340120001
```

---

# Verification

## SSH Path

```text
Windows PowerShell
      |
      v
Public EC2
      |
      v
Private EC2
```

## File Transfer

```text
prn.txt successfully copied from Public EC2 to Private EC2
```

## Security Validation

* Public EC2 accessible only from local machine.
* Private EC2 inaccessible directly from Internet.
* Private EC2 accessible only through Bastion Host.
* Secure file transfer verified.

---

# Conclusion

Successfully implemented a secure AWS VPC architecture using a Bastion Host. SSH access from Local Machine to Public EC2 and then to Private EC2 was verified. Secure file transfer between instances was completed successfully.
